## Name Conventions
- Choose the shortest possible name that uniquely identifies the entity or concept. The name is a label, not a definition — strip all unnecessary words.
- Never include parenthetical annotations, disambiguations, or qualifiers after the name. For example: "Struktur Notiz (MOC)" is forbidden — use just "Struktur Notiz". The name must stand on its own without parenthetical suffixes of any kind.

## Entities
Identify distinct, self-standing **things** mentioned in the source — the "nouns" of the text. An entity is a discrete, nameable, referable thing that exists independently of any single document: people, organizations, projects, products, tools, places, works, datasets, events, or systems.

**Decisive test:** If you can point to it and say "this is a [X]" (person, organization, tool, place…), it is an Entity. Entities answer *what* is being described.

**Entities are NOT patterns, methods, theories, frameworks, or abstract ideas — those are Concepts (see below).** If the item describes *how* something works, *why* something behaves a certain way, or *which* property something has, it belongs under Concepts, not Entities.

For each: provide the name, entityType (descriptive category: person / organization / project / product / tool / place / work / dataset / event / system), a concise description, and the exact source context (quote or context where it appears).

## Concepts
Identify abstract **ideas, theories, patterns, methods, frameworks, or discoveries** discussed in the source. Concepts are the "verbs and adjectives" of the wiki — they describe *how* things relate and *which* properties they have.

**Decisive test:** If the item is a way of doing something, a way of thinking about something, a category that classifies things, or a relationship pattern between entities — it is a Concept. Concepts answer *how* or *why*, not *what*.

**Concepts are NOT discrete, nameable things (persons, tools, places…) — those are Entities (see above).** Concepts are the connective tissue: they link entities together and explain their behavior.

Examples of concepts: Stoicism, praemeditatio malorum, confirmation bias, agile methodology, double-entry bookkeeping, the MAP kinase pathway.

For each: provide the name, domain (e.g. philosophy/psychology), a concise description, and the source context.
